The 'Keighley and Worth Valley Railway' is a branch line that served mills and
villages in the Worth Valley and is now a heritage railway line in West
Yorkshire, England. It runs from Keighley to Oxenhope. It
connects to the national rail network line at Keighley railway station.

It is currently one of only two heritage railways that operates a whole branch
line in its original form (the other being the Ecclesbourne Valley Railway at
Wirksworth, Derbyshire). It is one of the few heritage railways to provide real
ale on board some of its services.
